Much it were to be wiſhed, that along with the Tares, the Wheat had not alſo periſhed. But the general Syſtem of Manners being relaxed though refined; 
               See the Eſtimate, Part i. and Education ſtill left more and more imperfect; the Principle of Religion being unhappily deſtroyed among certain Ranks, and weakened among others; 
               Ib.—That of Honour being thus left to its own falſe and fantaſtic Dictates; Ib.—and Conſcience naturally following the Whims of its untutored Parent;—Licentiouſneſs and Faction, founded on a Want of Principle, cannot but ariſe, and ſtand among the 
                  "leading Characters of the preſent Times."
